European inflation dropped in food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the sharp rise in the price of food products.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, recording - after 2.6 per cent of October - an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent - the Office for Statistics of the Union based in Luxembourg announced.
Official forecasts were only probably 3 percent - Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian emission banks, did not cut the basic interest, its assumption that the decline, together with the rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would cause a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to maintain the inflation rate below, but at least about two per cent.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "there is a need to negotiate" on inflation so that it does not later have to intervene on this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 per cent, recorded in Germany, hit the 12-year record, while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation was fired in the euro area as a result of rising food and energy prices.
Wheat quotas increased by 88 per cent, and soybean quotas reached their maximum level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased by 52 per cent this year, reaching almost $100 per barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from 2.1 per cent to 2.5 per cent, in exchange for 2009 will already fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will be maintained in the next 3 or 4 months about 3 per cent, but the average annual rate will be 2.1 per cent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
