Many hospitals save themselves with disinfectants
This year several thousand infections have been reported in hospitals primarily due to the misuse of antibiotics.
Health conditions prevailing in hospitals, bedkeeping and overloading of staff do not favour the control of infections - says the medical-chief department of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it even saves itself with disinfectants.
Not long ago, a infection with MRSA has been diagnosed in the traumatology department of the János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of the bacteria resistant to antibiotics was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
An injury to a serious car accident was brought to his attention from the hospital and the same patient soon thereafter had to return to the hospital due to MRSA infection and since then has not been able to perform an important surgical intervention due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December of this year, the National System Nosocomialis Surveillance 1094 cases of hospital infection produced by multi-resistant agents have been registered - said Karolina Böröcz, head of the Department of National Centre for Epidemiology.
This means that hospitals have safely recorded this number of infections caused by multi-resistant agents, and there is no information.
About two thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, methicillin-oxicillin-resistant.
One third of human beings carry in their nose the staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria without causing any disease.
SA infections (e.g., inflammation of the throat, amigdalitis, skin infections, infections of wounds) respond well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once excessive or inappropriate application is made to antibiotics, bacteria that usually respond well to antibiotics, turn into very resistant bacteria to antibiotics and rapidly become infected in inadequate hospital conditions.
Serious hospital infections, such as infections of wounds or septicaemia, may be caused primarily in patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, in patients with impaired body, in elderly or in persons with low weight.
In the opinion of the medical director of the János Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are everyday in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotics resistant
"These patients are isolated, the nursing staff take care of them in rubber and mask gloves and there are appropriate antibiotics for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are previously examined to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but it is not possible to avoid infection in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent MRSA hospital infections in most cases, but the current national hospital circumstances do not favour the prevention of training and infection with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and homes of elders, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients who carry MRSA in their body.
However, the use of microbiological samples is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most of the cases come out in public light when the MRSA infections are already visible in the patient - said the departmental doctor of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes strict recommendations for the implementation of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat pathological infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapy should be directed, i.e. microbiological examinations should be made to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less frequent in the case of pregnant patients or in basic care - said Karolina Böröcz.
Saving with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected from one patient to another through health care.
Therefore, they play a very important role in washing hands, using rubber gloves and masks, but also in this sense there are significant deficiencies in hospitals.
MRSA was infected by casting and direct contact between individuals, but it was not always possible to isolate the infected patient under national hospital conditions.
Furthermore, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very attached, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least 1.5 metres away.
Unfortunately, it can also be experienced - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals with less favourable economic situation saves with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients, and that is why there is a greater likelihood of infection.
In Karolina Böröcz's view, where appropriate preventive measures are being taken, fewer infections of this type are reported or pathogen contamination can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
Treatment of contamination with MRSA is a huge cost to the National Fund for Disease Insurance, so in all countries it is fighting against it.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
The programme appears to be successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a downward trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
