EUR 400 million more for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three credit-limit agreements in Budapest on Friday at a total value of EUR 400 million to finance education, transport and environmental infrastructure, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance the Hungarian budget for transport and environmental protection projects, which will be carried out by the Cohesion Fund grant, of which the parties had previously signed a credit agreement of EUR 100 million, the contract they have just signed with respect to the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit agreement is also intended to finance the budget of educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for this objective of Hungary, on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million, the decision will be taken at a later date by extending the credit agreement.
The parties signed a contract for €50 million for innovation, which the budget will use mainly for the project of innovation and research at the University of Debrecen.
During the talks, they also covered the theme of the construction of the 4th line of the Metro.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary lasts with the EU the details of Metro financing, they would re-examine the subject whether or not it was necessary to amend the original contract and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this may take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990 the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest of the loans is in line with EURIBOR and the EIB offers an 8-year grace period, without charging a commission to keep the credit at the disposal of the debtor.
