Fodor and the six by hundreds of Hungarians
According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gabor Fodor, the meetings at the expert level will be concluded on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official opening will continue the ministerial negotiations on the international climate regime beyond 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are discussing the Balí Road Sheet, which is available on post-emission reduction efforts, established in the Kyoto Protocol, which is in force until 2012.
There are lively discussions on the particular nature of developing countries and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that it does not wish to negotiate precise figures for the moment, although it tends to agree that, compared to the 1990 situation, greenhouse gas emissions will decline by 25 to 40 per cent by 2020.
Another major theme of the conference is whether industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are or are not willing to provide material and technological assistance to countries in need.
In addition, an agreement was reached on aid to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be directed by a 16-member management board, probably within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes "Piac es Profit".
The six per cent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister for Environment and Hydrology Gabor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to preserve its avant-garde role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 compared to 1990, whether or not the "after-2012 agreement" will be signed, and is willing to commit to a decline of 30 per cent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in line with their responsibilities and capacities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the signatory countries of the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed to decrease by 5.2 per cent, within which the 15 EU Member States committed to achieve 8 per cent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce the emissions of greenhouse gases by 6 percent over the period 1985-87, which our country will fulfil - it notes the press release from the Ministry of the Environment.
It is a great deal at stake in Balí, since in two years the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed, because if not, its entry into force would be delayed by 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments entered into in the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system, the need of which was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, the United Nations' international scientific association dealing with climate change, which obtained the Nobel Peace Prize.
Thus, the reduction of emissions would be delayed and an increase of more than 2° C of the earth's average temperature could not be prevented, since scientists believe it would have irreversible and irreversible consequences.
British Army Recruited on YouTube
The units of the British army in a video distributor publish recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First, the British Air Force (RAD) was the one who took advantage of YouTube services: special units moving to Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos about their actions against the Taliban - the BBC reported.
These tapes made with mini cameras mounted on helmets are controlled in the general body of Kandahar operations, then sent to London to be loaded on the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
There are 139 recordings from air force soldiers who have been loaded in this way on the Internet and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered in the spring of 2007 under the name "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions carried out in Iraq and Afghanistan, while both the British Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the Air Force had loaded the videos with recruitment goals, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defence they also served to present to the public the true objective of the presence of the British army abroad.
This kind of propaganda almost costs nothing compared to conventional recruitment television spots - the expert in defence Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC - in return, inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for the military actions decided by the government.
Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the reticulously edited and censored recordings, there are also popular videos in the distributor, such as about the death of soldiers: in the "official" advertising films, a bit of hypocrites, officials speak as much of loss, but not as much as the bloody part of the fight.
In addition, many videos have already been uploaded on the Internet from the battle camps of Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruiting with video games of shooting, free downloadable, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can directly replace the soldiers.
