New fears about gas between Russia and Ukraine
The growing dispute over the price of gas between Ukraine and Russia increases the risk of affecting the export of fuel to Western Europe by Russia.
Most of the gas exported by Russia to the European Union (EU) is directed through Ukraine, so each rock between the two nations is a source of attention.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price of gas, Russia will have to pay higher traffic rates.
A previous dispute last year reduced supplies to EU states.
The last dispute between Kiev and Moscow came with the Ukrainian government and the Russian state, the monopoly owner of gas, Gazprom, trying to agree on the amount of money that Ukraine should pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom said it would charge more to Ukraine, as it has committed to paying an extra 50% in 2008 for the gas coming from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say it might be that Ukraine pays 40 per cent more for Gazprom imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transits during the talks," Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told the Reuters News Agency.
"Changes in gas prices should not relate to our arguments on the levels of transit rates [to Western Europe] via Ukraine."
The last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom cut supply to Ukraine in January 2006.
This meant a drop in exports to Western Europe, which quickly increased prices.
Russian gas represents the fourth part of the EU supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it is not yet fully developed.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own supply with Turkmenistan gas and other former Soviet nations in Central Asia.
NHS "should try foreign workers"
The Scottish NHS needs to monitor the criminal record of employees outside Europe, one observer said.
The recommendation of General Auditor Robert Black came after it was found that a foreign doctor was related to the attack at Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also showed concern that the Scottish NHS does not have an accurate understanding of the amount of foreign personnel it has.
However, his report pointed out other controls that were carried out correctly through a sample of five health authorities.
The auditor-general checked the number of foreign personnel hired outside the European economic area, as a result of attacks at Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after hitting a jeep at the doors of the terminal building at the airport.
He was one of the three doctors who acted at the Old Bailey by video conference in October, accused of alleged car bomb attacks in the United Kingdom.
NHS expects to carry out pre-employment checks for candidates to ensure that they meet the qualifications, experience and authorization to work in the United Kingdom.
Although the Scottish Health Board uses "Disclosure Scotland" to carry out criminal background checks, the agency has no jurisdiction to obtain this information outside Britain.
The auditor-general's report recommends, inter alia, that the Boards should be guided by the Criminal Records Bureau, which helps employers with criminal controls in many countries outside Britain.
"Although we find some of the personal records with evidence of these controls, this is not a routine review," says the report.
Black states that the Scottish NHS has a high level of compliance with its own employment policies, but notes that: "Our report highlights areas that can be improved to ensure that the necessary information is available in the number of NHS foreign staff."
The president of BMA Scotland, Dr. Peter Terry said it was "very unlikely" that pre-employment checks could identify potential NHS employees who could commit terrorist acts in the future.
"The report suggests that pre-employment checks work in NHS Scotland but it is not clear what is the added value of the recommendations made," he explained.
The Scottish health authorities declare that they currently have 1,161 foreign persons, most of them doctors and nurses.
But the auditor-general warned that the number could be higher, in part because the boards have problems identifying who the employees are with indefinite residence permits.
The investigation also found that the verification procedures established by the NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian were being carried out extensively.
This includes passport controls, work permit and qualification check.
The Scottish government is currently reviewing the policy and pre-employment guide of foreigners in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "I had a great interest in this work as a result of the terrorist attack at Glasgow Airport.
He added that the Scottish government, together with the Health Boards, could consider the recommendations of the reports and that this would be reflected in the update of the pre-employment control guides for all working groups - including foreigners - which they planned to publish next month.
