Venus climate can give an idea of the future of Earth
Venus could have once been a suitable place for life, scientists said yesterday.
The data of a European spacecraft in orbit showed the planet more like a gem of the Earth than it had previously observed.
Venus is the closest planet to Earth.
Both planets have similar size and occupy similar orbits, although Venus is slightly closer to the sun.
Millions of years ago, Venus could have had conditions similar to those that made the Earth a habitable planet, scientists now believe.
But the effects of carbon dioxide and the greenhouse effect, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation and slower solar rotation sent Venus to a very different type of development.
Today the planet has no water, the surface temperature is enough to melt lead and is eroded by hurricane winds and lightning storms.
The results of the European Space Agency for Venus Express, which has studied the planet for a year, provide an overview of how the Earth could develop catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor, of the University of Oxford Department of Physics and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, says: "It is being clarified why the climate in Venus is so different from that of Earth, when there are two similar planets.
"Our new data make it possible to build a scene in which Venus began as Earth, possibly with a habitable environment millions of years ago."
