Venus: twin brother of the Earth.
Although its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the most like planet on Earth, something that has not yet been raised. The European Venus Express probe discovered rays in the atmosphere and remolons in the poles, the same ones that appear in winter on Earth.
For three decades now, researchers suspected that there might be rays in Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it has discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. In Venus the rays warm at a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell from the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific journal Nature.
According to the famous model of Urey-Miller's life, the rays caused life on Earth: the storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, for their part, had caused amino acids that were the basic components of life.
In Venus it's not like this: if there was ever life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution," explains Sean Solomon of the Washington Carnegie Institute.
Today, there can be no life on the surface of Venus: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times greater than on Earth and on the surface it has temperatures of 500°C, oscilulating so that temperatures can be reached below zero.
"Perhaps Venus is a "diabolic" twin from Earth, but still a twin," said Russell.
The main objective of the "Venus Express" mission is to answer the question why Venus, so much like Earth for its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since there were no special missions since the 1990s, only for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus research.
The latest results of the research that will be presented in many articles of "Nature", according to researchers, not only underline Venus' uniqueness in the Solar System.
"This also shows that neighbouring planets have more common characteristics with the Earth than we had expected," ESA reports.
Despite the already well-known stormy winds in the North Pole, researchers have also discovered in the southern polar region a vertice formed by the clouds that rotate faster.
This phenomenon recalls the wind currents in the high ground atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers by Giuseppe Picconi of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to Earth and its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers is almost as large.
This planet also called the star of dawn or the star of evening orbit around the Sun almost 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: a day in Venus is 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars is not much like Earth, scientists start from the basis that both planets had been formed under the same conditions.
The two planets had accumulated water that remained on the Earth in the oceans, but in Venus it was dissociated in the universe.
While carbon dioxide had become carbon stones on Earth, Venus formed most of the atmosphere.
